            {
              "id": "ConfusingTernary",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Avoid if (x != y) ..; else ..;"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nAvoid negation within an \"if\" expression with an \"else\" clause.  For example, rephrase:\n`if (x != y) diff(); else same();` as: `if (x == y) same(); else diff();`.\n\nMost \"if (x != y)\" cases without an \"else\" are often return cases, so consistent use of this\nrule makes the code easier to read.  Also, this resolves trivial ordering problems, such\nas \"does the error case go first?\" or \"does the common case go first?\".\n\nSince null checks are commonly considered a positive condition, they are by default ignored\nby this rule. This means both `a == null` and `a != null` are allowed. If you want\nto enforce either style and disallow the other, use the property `nullCheckBranch`.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_codestyle.html#confusingternary",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nAvoid negation within an \"if\" expression with an \"else\" clause.  For example, rephrase:\n`if (x != y) diff(); else same();` as: `if (x == y) same(); else diff();`.\n\nMost \"if (x != y)\" cases without an \"else\" are often return cases, so consistent use of this\nrule makes the code easier to read.  Also, this resolves trivial ordering problems, such\nas \"does the error case go first?\" or \"does the common case go first?\".\n\nSince null checks are commonly considered a positive condition, they are by default ignored\nby this rule. This means both `a == null` and `a != null` are allowed. If you want\nto enforce either style and disallow the other, use the property `nullCheckBranch`.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Code Style",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Code Style"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "MethodArgumentCouldBeFinal",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Parameter 'path' is not assigned and could be declared final"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\n            Reports method and constructor parameters that can be made final because they are never reassigned within the body of the method.\n\n            This rule ignores unused parameters so as not to overlap with the rule {% rule java/bestpractices/UnusedFormalParameter %}.\n            It will also ignore the parameters of abstract methods.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_codestyle.html#methodargumentcouldbefinal",
              "help": {
                "text": "\n            Reports method and constructor parameters that can be made final because they are never reassigned within the body of the method.\n\n            This rule ignores unused parameters so as not to overlap with the rule {% rule java/bestpractices/UnusedFormalParameter %}.\n            It will also ignore the parameters of abstract methods.\n        "
              },
